<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Questionable status. In the Mediterranean only reported from Greece (
<bibRefCitation author="Bogdanos, Costantinos" journalOrPublisher="Thalassographica" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="77 - 105" title="The macrozoobenthos of an Aegean Embayment" volume="6" year="1983">Bogdanos and Satsmadjis 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Commonly distributed in West Atlantic and South-West Africa. 
<bibRefCitation author="Arvanitidis, Christos" journalOrPublisher="PhD thesis. Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Thessaloniki" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="Συστηματική και βιονομική μελέτη των μακροβενθικών πολυxαίτων (AnnelidaPolychaeta) του Βορείου Αιγαίου" year="1994">Arvanitidis (1994)</bibRefCitation>
regards its presence in the Mediterranean as doubtful. 
<bibRefCitation author="Day, John H" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="463 - 560" title="The Polychaete Fauna of South Africa. Part 6. Sedentary species dredged off Cape coasts with a few new records from the shore" volume="44" year="1961">Day (1961)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Day, John H" journalOrPublisher="Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="A monograph on the Polychaeta of Southern Africa. Part 1. Errantia" year="1967">Day (1967)</bibRefCitation>
include it in the subgroup of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Prionospio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Prionospio" order="Spionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Prionospio</taxonomicName>
species with apinnate branchiae. Maciolek in her unpublished dissertation (
<bibRefCitation author="Maciolek Blake, N. J." journalOrPublisher="Boston University, Boston" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="Systematics of Atlantic Spionidae (Annelida: Polychaeta) with special reference to deep-water species" year="1983">Maciolek Blake 1983</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Jamar, E." journalOrPublisher="Boletin Instituto Espanol de Oceanografia" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="107 - 110" title="Primera cita para el litoral de la Peninsula Iberica del genero Aonidella (Polychaeta: Spionidae), con una redescription de la especie Aonidelladayi Maciolek 1983" volume="5" year="1989">Lopez-Jamar (1989)</bibRefCitation>
moved it to a new genus (
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Aonidella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aonidella" order="Spionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Aonidella</taxonomicName>
) on the basis of other unique diagnostic characters (for more information see 
<bibRefCitation author="Maciolek, N. J." journalOrPublisher="Bulletin Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="529 - 547" title="New species and records of Aonidella, Laonice, and Spiophanes (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from shelf and slope depths of the Western North Atlantic" volume="67" year="2000">Maciolek 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Re-examination of the material would be required to investigate the possible assignment of the Greek record to a 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Prionospio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Prionospio (Minuspio)" order="Spionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Minuspio">Prionospio (Minuspio)</taxonomicName>
species with apinnate branchiae.
</paragraph>
